<h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #00ccff;"><strong>Philosophy of Life and Death in the East</strong></span></h2>
<span style="color: #808080;"><span style="color: #808080;">The <span style="color: #00ccff;"><strong>Confucian</strong></span> view </span>of life and death centers on honoring life, accepting death with peace, and defining one’s fate through ren (benevolence). Death is not the ultimate question to be resolved, but rather the completion and validation of an ethical life. It is through the eternity of ren that one overcomes the fear of the perishable body. Death becomes the period at the end of a life of moral practice—its value determined by the virtues cultivated in life.</span>

<span style="color: #808080;">The <span style="color: #00ccff;"><strong>Daoist</strong></span> view of life and death, by contrast, centers on following the flow of transformation and returning to nature. Life and death are but ordinary moments in the universe’s natural cycle; one should let go of attachment and fear. Death is a comma—a return to the source—and its meaning lies not in resistance, but in acceptance.</span>
